@exceptionfactory I just found this helpful [tutorial](https://www.myonlinetraininghub.com/excel-date-and-time#:~:text=When%20you%20look%20at%20a,decimal%20portion%20is%20the%20time.) which explains how dates and times are stored in Excel. Based on this information I believe we can provide better inferences when the cell type is numeric and is date formatted. If its a whole number we know its date, if its a fraction we know its a time and if its a whole  number with a fraction then its a timestamp. Hence lines 81-84 in `StandardCellFieldTypeReader` can be expanded to incorporate this logic to identify the most precise type (DATE, TIME or TIMESTAMP).


e.g. (Which probably would look better incorporated in its own method)
  ```
if (DateUtil.isCellDateFormatted(cell)) {
               final double numericCellValue = cell.getNumericCellValue();
               if (numericCellValue > 0 && numericCellValue < 1;) {
                    dataType = RecordFieldType.TIME.getDataType();
               } else {
                    final long roundedCellValue = (long) numericCellValue;
                    if (roundedCellValue == numericCellValue) {
                      dataType = RecordFieldType.DATE.getDataType();
                    } else {
                      dataType = RecordFieldType.TIMESTAMP.getDataType();
                  }
             }
       }
```

